content.description:
Fun climb that has a burly crux. I took the liberty of inflating the grade. 

Bolt line to the right of Where’s the beach. 
Bolts (bring 8 ish draws) chains with steel lower offs

follow the brown rock arching left with nice moves to a bolted anchor.



At the lower part of Muscle beach head right just before reaching the scramble to go up the the upper part of muscle beach. This route is the second to last from the right of the wall. 

8 bolts

climbs.name: Beached Whale
climbs.fa: Prep: Cody Leyden, FA: Adam Tutte, 2011

content.description:
Start with a powerfull boulder problem, then reach the obvious massive 8 meters horizontal roof with juggy holds, take a rest and power through the roof with heel hooks until you can slot your whole body into the gap in the roof (I guess thats where the name of the route came from haha), enjoy the rest and finish by passing the lip on crimpy holds to a bolted belay station.



Start on the obvious triangular overhang just left of the acces of the upper part of the cliff. Also look for the massive horizontal roof that has a big gap. 

Bolts

Steep climbing on big holds. Quite powerful with long moves. 



to the left of the big orange boulder.

7 bolts

Start just below at the left end of the low roof, then slowly diagonal right until you reach the bolted anchors. 



At the lower part of Muscle beach head right just before reaching the scramble to go up the the upper part of muscle beach. This route is the second from the left part of the wall.

8 bolts

climbs.name: Where to Toss at the Beach

content.description:
It’s all about the jugs!  Work your way up a left facing flake feature with an interesting combination of laybacking,scums, and kneebars until you get to the obvious crux.  Some will dyno, some will heel hook, and some will go static; all fun options.  Traverse right at the sixth bolt to join Where’s the Beach.  

On the left side of the large orange boulder sitting on Muscle Beach upper.
Fixed chains

What a terrific 5.12a!  Great movement. Nothing is too crazy or too hard. The finish is rather puzzling and funky getting from the last permadraw to the chains. Savor the rest! 

Starts on the right side of the crag on top of a 5 foot high large square boulder
One quickdraw and the rest are permadraws
A newly developed crag that's exactly what you would expect from the name. Gymnastic, pumpy, difficult routes.
